# Model & Subagent Routing

Cursor does not auto-route by task complexity — model choice for the main thread is a
manual/UI decision, and `model` is an explicit argument on every `Task` call. Apply this
table deliberately; don't default to the same model for every request.

## Main thread (this session)

| Signal | Recommendation |
|--------|----------------|
| Trivial: quick lookup, rename, format, boilerplate, simple Q&A | Switch to a fast/cheap model (e.g. `composer-2.5-fast`) or accept `Auto` |
| Standard coding (most tasks) | `Auto`, or a mid-tier thinking model (e.g. `claude-4.6-sonnet-medium-thinking`) |
| Deep reasoning: architecture, hard bugs, security/correctness-critical, multi-file refactors | A frontier thinking model (`claude-opus-4-8-thinking-high`, `claude-sonnet-5-thinking-high`, or `gpt-5.5-medium`) — also prefer **Plan Mode** first |
| Coding-specialized deep task (large diff, codegen-heavy) | `gpt-5.3-codex` |
| Beyond-frontier: multi-day/long-horizon autonomous work, or Opus-tier already stalled/looped on the problem | `claude-fable-5-thinking-high` — Anthropic's Mythos-class tier, above Opus. Notably more expensive; escalate to it, don't default to it |

If unsure, prefer `Auto` over guessing — it already balances cost/quality. Only hand-pick
when the task is clearly at one end of the spectrum.

## Auto-escalation (advisor-tool replication)

Cursor has no server-side "advisor" primitive like Claude Code's — there's no mechanism
that consults a stronger model mid-generation on its own. Approximate it by treating a
`Task` call to a frontier model as your on-demand second opinion, and self-trigger it at
the same moments Claude Code's advisor tool would fire:

- **Before committing to an approach** on an ambiguous or high-stakes change
- **When stuck on a recurring error** — a `postToolUse` hook (`.cursor/hooks/advisor-escalate.sh`)
  deterministically nudges this one: after the same tool call fails identically 3 times,
  it injects `additional_context` telling you to escalate. Don't ignore that nudge —
  stop retrying the same way and spawn the Task it suggests.
- **Before declaring a hard/ambiguous task done** — no hook enforces this one (Cursor
  hooks don't reliably support blocking on session completion); it's judgment-based, so
  apply it yourself on non-trivial tasks.

When escalating, spawn a `Task` with `model: claude-opus-4-8-thinking-high` for most
cases, or `claude-fable-5-thinking-high` only if the problem looks genuinely hard/ambiguous
even for Opus-tier. Feed it the relevant context (error text, files touched, what's been
tried) and ask specifically for root cause / a corrected approach — not a redo of the
whole task. Apply its guidance, then continue; don't hand off the rest of the task to it
unless the guidance says the approach itself needs to change.

## Task subagents (`model` param)

Only pass an explicit `model` when the subagent's job is consistently at one end of the
spectrum. Omit it (inherit default) for variable-complexity work.

| Subagent job | Model |
|---|---|
| Mechanical, narrow, well-defined (build-fix loops, config parsing/migration, formatting) | `composer-2.5-fast` |
| General research / exploration / most `generalPurpose` tasks | `claude-sonnet-5-thinking-high` or omit (default) |
| Deep reasoning: security review, adversarial review, subtle-bug hunting, architecture review | `claude-opus-4-8-thinking-high` |
| Large/complex codegen or refactor subagent | `gpt-5.3-codex` |
| Escalation only: an Opus-tier subagent already failed/looped on a genuinely hard, long-horizon problem | `claude-fable-5-thinking-high` — reserve for rare cases, not routine delegation |

## Subagent usage (when to delegate at all)

Use `Task` when the work is:
- Independent and parallelizable with other work (batch multiple `Task` calls in one message)
- A specialized review (`bugbot`, `security-review`, `database-reviewer`, etc.) that benefits from isolation
- Large enough in scope that it would otherwise dominate the main thread's context

Don't spawn a subagent for single-file, few-step edits — do it directly. Never delegate
the entire user request just to "return the result" (see `Task` tool guidance).
